- What you're describing is the need for,

00:51:24.510 --> 00:51:27.600
I'll call it, a mediating class of people

00:51:27.600 --> 00:51:30.700
who know the science and

00:51:30.700 --> 00:51:32.900
who have worked in the political process

00:51:32.900 --> 00:51:35.810
and part of their task would be

00:51:35.810 --> 00:51:37.114
to create the narratives

00:51:37.114 --> 00:51:40.420
that make sense for the political leaders.

00:51:40.420 --> 00:51:42.110
Is that fair?
- It's only part

00:51:42.110 --> 00:51:44.380
of the problem because, there
are a certain number of these.

00:51:44.380 --> 00:51:46.650
There are people who get
their science degrees,

00:51:46.650 --> 00:51:49.250
go become congressional fellows,

00:51:49.250 --> 00:51:53.430
are staffed to different
types of elected officials,

00:51:53.430 --> 00:51:55.960
and have been in that
sort of interpretive role.

00:51:55.960 --> 00:51:58.880
So we've sort of already
got that function.

00:51:58.880 --> 00:52:02.180
What we don't have is the scientist

00:52:02.180 --> 00:52:04.113
willing to reach out to meet them.

00:52:04.990 --> 00:52:06.480
So it's more than saying,

00:52:06.480 --> 00:52:08.350
we need someone to interpret it.

00:52:08.350 --> 00:52:12.000
Often we're trying to
create scientific products

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:14.550
that better address the answers.

00:52:14.550 --> 00:52:17.060
So, what I've done here,

00:52:17.060 --> 00:52:19.620
we have our scientists
saying what the risks are.

00:52:19.620 --> 00:52:22.700
We have people in the political sphere

00:52:22.700 --> 00:52:25.570
that can accept science.

00:52:25.570 --> 00:52:28.260
But we needed to make
this product that said,

00:52:28.260 --> 00:52:30.682
here's what the implications

00:52:30.682 --> 00:52:33.023
of these scientific hazards are.

00:52:35.410 --> 00:52:37.710
We sometimes call it risk translation,

00:52:37.710 --> 00:52:40.600
how to go from the hazards to the risk,

00:52:40.600 --> 00:52:42.950
which is an interdisciplinary

00:52:42.950 --> 00:52:45.713
scientific development process.

00:52:47.080 --> 00:52:49.260
It's because it's so interdisciplinary,

00:52:49.260 --> 00:52:52.070
it's very hard to get it moving,

00:52:52.070 --> 00:52:54.610
or who has the mission for it?

00:52:54.610 --> 00:52:56.960
The US Geological Survey
has supported me doing this,

00:52:56.960 --> 00:53:00.570
but, fundamentally, our
mission is the hazards.

00:53:00.570 --> 00:53:03.830
I push the comfort zone by
going in in this direction

00:53:03.830 --> 00:53:06.630
and we're making a decision now.

00:53:06.630 --> 00:53:08.620
Society needs it too much.

00:53:08.620 --> 00:53:10.250
We have to keep on going.

00:53:10.250 --> 00:53:12.540
But it's an uncomfortable process.

00:53:12.540 --> 00:53:16.080
- You have talked about communication.

00:53:16.080 --> 00:53:18.920
You've talked about
the failings of science

00:53:18.920 --> 00:53:21.170
with regard to this dimension (mumbles).

00:53:21.170 --> 00:53:24.020
What about leadership,
political leadership?

00:53:24.020 --> 00:53:25.230
You've worked with the mayor.

00:53:25.230 --> 00:53:27.640
That experience was very successful.

00:53:27.640 --> 00:53:31.120
Can you identify some
of the characteristics

00:53:31.120 --> 00:53:34.040
that you think political leaders

00:53:34.040 --> 00:53:36.920
will have to have in the
future to manage this?

00:53:36.920 --> 00:53:38.890
They're gonna have to
have a science education

00:53:38.890 --> 00:53:43.500
it sounds like, but also, be sensitive to

00:53:43.500 --> 00:53:47.420
the kinds of solutions
and the political costs

00:53:47.420 --> 00:53:49.250
in navigating that terrain.

00:53:49.250 --> 00:53:51.290
- I think that what we need is

00:53:52.220 --> 00:53:56.540
intelligence to be able to
make all of these connections.

00:53:56.540 --> 00:54:00.700
And, a commitment to a future vision.

00:54:00.700 --> 00:54:04.603
To be able to move beyond
just the election cycle.

00:54:05.610 --> 00:54:07.910
I'd say, in general, we're seeing

00:54:07.910 --> 00:54:10.623
a certain amount of
this at the city level.

00:54:12.130 --> 00:54:14.150
Mayor Garcetti loved to tout a book called

00:54:14.150 --> 00:54:16.440
If Mayors Ruled the World,

00:54:16.440 --> 00:54:18.373
which is just a recent analysis of,

00:54:19.500 --> 00:54:21.710
sort of where the progressive, innovative

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:25.290
stuff is happening is
often in these, the mayors

00:54:25.290 --> 00:54:27.170
especially in the larger cities.

00:54:27.170 --> 00:54:30.633
Because once you get up to
higher levels of government,

00:54:31.900 --> 00:54:33.360
I think there's sort of more

00:54:33.360 --> 00:54:35.370
tensions pulling in different directions.

00:54:35.370 --> 00:54:38.370
You get to the federal
level, we're a money,

00:54:38.370 --> 00:54:40.810
feds tend to be a money source,

00:54:40.810 --> 00:54:42.980
but it's very hard to do a solution

00:54:42.980 --> 00:54:45.940
because it's just too big a problem.

00:54:45.940 --> 00:54:47.590
And, especially, when you look at

00:54:48.500 --> 00:54:50.343
issues around natural disasters.

00:54:51.210 --> 00:54:52.710
The rate of earthquakes is not increasing,

00:54:52.710 --> 00:54:55.560
but the number of people
living in earthquake areas is.

00:54:55.560 --> 00:54:58.270
And the rate of meteorologic
disasters is going up.

00:54:58.270 --> 00:55:01.363
This is going to be a
major issue in our future.

00:55:02.780 --> 00:55:06.270
The emergency managers like to
say, all disasters are local.

00:55:06.270 --> 00:55:08.900
In the end, it's what
happens in your community.

00:55:08.900 --> 00:55:12.122
It's individuals and neighborhoods.

00:55:12.122 --> 00:55:15.423
If all disasters are local,
all resilience is local too.

00:55:16.270 --> 00:55:18.220
If we really wanna get this through,

00:55:18.220 --> 00:55:22.083
it's about my pipes, my buildings,

00:55:23.260 --> 00:55:25.570
and my neighborhood and my community,

00:55:25.570 --> 00:55:29.610
and, will life be so
awful that my community

00:55:29.610 --> 00:55:31.820
is no longer worth staying with?

00:55:31.820 --> 00:55:35.800
So it's both dealing with the
very practical physical things

00:55:35.800 --> 00:55:38.597
but also, making it a community
that people wanna stay in

00:55:38.597 --> 00:55:41.510
that's worth fighting for
and is worth helping recover,

00:55:41.510 --> 00:55:43.580
'cause it's not gonna be easy.

00:55:43.580 --> 00:55:46.120
- Well, on that note, Dr.
Jones, I wanna thank you.

00:55:46.120 --> 00:55:48.640
And, by the way, I wanna congratulate you

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:51.760
because, for all of your
work, you were just awarded

00:55:51.760 --> 00:55:55.420
the Samuel J. Heyman
Service to America Medal

00:55:57.570 --> 00:56:01.670
in Citizen Services last
week for your work in LA.

00:56:01.670 --> 00:56:03.559
- It was really amazing.

00:56:03.559 --> 00:56:04.880
As I said, I thought that I was

00:56:04.880 --> 00:56:07.630
walking away from recognition

00:56:07.630 --> 00:56:09.880
'cause I just saw it
as too important to do,

00:56:09.880 --> 00:56:12.330
and it's been very satisfying,

00:56:12.330 --> 00:56:15.330
as some of these accolades
have come through

00:56:15.330 --> 00:56:18.150
and recognizing people want,

00:56:18.150 --> 00:56:20.360
People want science.

00:56:20.360 --> 00:56:21.860
We can make a difference and

00:56:21.860 --> 00:56:23.550
we just have to figure out how to

00:56:23.550 --> 00:56:25.700
bridge the gap in communication.

00:56:25.700 --> 00:56:28.220
- Well, on that very positive note,

00:56:28.220 --> 00:56:30.440
thank you very much for
being on our program.

00:56:30.440 --> 00:56:32.667
And thank you very much for joining us

00:56:32.667 --> 00:56:35.358
for this Conversation with History.

